    <article class="prose-editorial cs-body" set:html={`<h2>Educational Case Study Disclosure</h2><p>This case study is hypothetical and for educational purposes only. Scenarios, borrower profiles, loan terms, interest rates, and outcomes are illustrative examples and do not represent current offers or guaranteed terms.</p><p>For specific details including down payment requirements, closing cost estimates, interest rate details, closing cost breakdowns, payment calculations, cash-to-close estimates, or an official Loan Estimate, it is highly recommended you<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call/"> schedule a meeting with one of our licensed mortgage advisors</a>.</p><p><b>Learn more:</b></p><ul><li><a href="https://www.consumerfinance.gov/rules-policy/regulations/1026/24/">Bank statement loan cash-out refinance Reg Z advertising requirements (§1026.24)</a> – CFPB official regulation</li><li><a href="https://www.ecfr.gov/current/title-12/chapter-X/part-1026">Bank statement loan cash-out refinance Reg Z full text and compliance</a> – Electronic Code of Federal Regulations</li><li><a href="https://www.consumerfinance.gov/rules-policy/regulations/1026/interp-24/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Official bank statement loan cash-out refinance advertising interpretations (§1026.24)</a> – CFPB interpretations</li><li><a href="https://www.ecfr.gov/current/title-12/chapter-X/part-1014" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Bank statement loan cash-out refinance MAP Rule (Reg N) mortgage advertising</a> – Mortgage advertising rules</li><li><a href="https://www.nmlsconsumeraccess.org/">NMLS Consumer Access – Verify bank statement loan cash-out refinance lender licensure</a></li></ul><p>Actual loan terms vary by credit profile, property, occupancy, location, market conditions, and lender guidelines. For current options tailored to you,<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call/"> schedule a consultation</a> or<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/same-day-approval/"> apply online</a>.</p><p>Ready to explore your options?<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call/"> Schedule a call</a> with a loan advisor.</p>		
					<h2>How This Bank Statement Loan Cash-Out Refinance Funded Strategic Growth Using Business Deposits</h2>				
		<p>Rachel M., a 46-year-old boutique clothing store owner in Naples, had successfully operated her retail business for 14 years, building a loyal customer base and establishing her brand as a destination for upscale women's fashion. As an established business owner (Step 3 in her financial journey, having transitioned from building her business to optimizing and expanding it), Rachel was ready to open a second location in a high-traffic shopping district where several national retailers had recently announced new stores, signaling strong consumer spending and foot traffic potential—a strategic move toward building a multi-location retail brand that could eventually provide generational wealth for her family.</p><p>Opening a second retail location required substantial capital for lease deposits, initial inventory purchases, store fixtures and displays, point-of-sale systems, hiring and training staff, and covering operating expenses during the ramp-up period before the new location reached profitability. Rachel had built substantial equity in her primary residence through years of appreciation and mortgage paydown. A cash-out refinance would provide the capital she needed at favorable terms compared to business loans, which carried significantly higher rates and required personal guarantees that would limit her financial flexibility.</p><p>However, Rachel's tax returns presented a significant obstacle. Like most retail business owners, her accountant maximized legitimate business deductions—inventory costs, commercial rent, utilities, employee payroll, marketing expenses, equipment depreciation, insurance, professional fees, and other operating costs—resulting in significantly reduced taxable income on her Schedule C despite the substantial monthly deposits consistently flowing into her business bank account from sales revenue.</p><p>When Rachel approached three conventional refinance lenders for cash-out refinancing, all rejected her application within days after reviewing her tax returns. The lenders focused exclusively on her taxable income rather than the strong consistent business deposits her retail operation generated month after month. This wasn't just about one refinance—it threatened her entire business expansion strategy and her ability to capitalize on the prime retail location opportunity before another tenant secured the space.</p><p>Facing similar challenges?<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call/"> Schedule a call</a> to explore your options.</p><h2><b>The Challenge: Why Traditional Cash-Out Refinance Lenders Rejected This Profitable Business Owner</b></h2><p>Rachel approached three conventional cash-out refinance lenders confident that her strong financial position would make approval straightforward. She had built substantial equity in her home through years of appreciation and consistent mortgage payments. Her retail business generated strong consistent revenue with healthy profit margins. She maintained excellent credit with spotless payment history across all accounts. She had clear expansion plans with detailed financial projections showing how the second location would perform based on her existing store's proven track record.</p><h3><b>Why Did Traditional Lenders Reject Rachel's Bank Statement Loan Cash-Out Refinance Application?</b></h3><p>Yet all three lenders delivered the same verdict after reviewing her tax returns: insufficient income to qualify for the cash-out refinance amount she needed.</p><p>The disconnect was stark and deeply frustrating. Rachel's business bank account received substantial deposits every month from retail sales—credit card transactions, cash sales, online orders, and special event purchases. Her monthly deposit patterns showed consistent, predictable revenue with seasonal peaks during holidays and special promotions. Any objective analysis of her bank statements would confirm she ran a profitable, stable business with strong cash flow supporting both her personal expenses and business operations.</p><p>But her tax returns told a completely different story. After her accountant applied all legitimate business deductions—cost of goods sold for inventory purchases, commercial lease payments, employee wages and payroll taxes, utilities, insurance, marketing and advertising costs, equipment depreciation, credit card processing fees, professional services, and other operating expenses—her Schedule C showed significantly reduced adjusted gross income. From the lenders' perspective focused solely on tax returns, Rachel appeared to have insufficient income to support a larger mortgage payment after cash-out.</p><h3><b>How Did Tax-Efficient Planning Prevent Bank Statement Loan Cash-Out Refinance Approval?</b></h3><p>"I felt completely trapped by smart financial planning," Rachel explained. "My accountant had structured my business perfectly to minimize my tax liability through every legitimate deduction available. I was saving substantial amounts in taxes every year—money I could reinvest in inventory, marketing, or now, expansion. But those same tax-saving strategies were now preventing me from accessing my own home equity to grow my business. The system penalized me for being financially smart."</p><p>The qualification gap was substantial. Rachel needed to refinance her existing mortgage and access significant cash-out proceeds to fund her second location opening. Traditional lenders calculated her qualifying income based solely on her taxable income shown on tax returns. That calculation determined she could only qualify for significantly less than she needed—nowhere near enough to both refinance her existing balance and pull out the capital required for business expansion.</p><h3><b>What Bank Statement Loan Cash-Out Refinance Qualification Gap Did Rachel Face?</b></h3><p>"The math didn't work with conventional lenders," Rachel said. "They looked at my tax returns after all my business deductions and said I didn't make enough money to qualify for the cash-out amount I needed. But my business bank statements clearly showed I had more than enough income. The disconnect was absurd—they were ignoring the actual evidence of my business success sitting right there in my deposit history."</p><p>The timing pressure added significant urgency to Rachel's situation. The prime retail space she'd identified was attracting interest from other potential tenants. The landlord wanted a decision quickly and preferred tenants who could move fast on lease signing and buildout. Rachel had already invested time and resources into business planning, market research, and preliminary discussions with the property owner. Losing this location would set her expansion plans back significantly and potentially allow a competitor to secure the space.</p><h3><b>Why Was Bank Statement Loan Cash-Out Refinance More Favorable Than Business Loans?</b></h3><p>Additionally, Rachel had concerns about alternative funding options. Business loans for retail expansion carried substantially higher interest rates compared to mortgage cash-out refinancing. Equipment financing and inventory lines of credit added complexity and often required personal guarantees that would encumber her other assets. Small Business Administration loans involved extensive paperwork and lengthy approval timelines that wouldn't meet her immediate needs. Home equity offered the most cost-effective capital source—if she could just access it.</p><p>"I needed a solution that looked at my real business performance, not just my tax-optimized returns," Rachel explained. "Every month my business generated strong deposits. Every month I paid all my bills on time. Every month I demonstrated financial responsibility and business success. But conventional lenders couldn't see past my tax returns to understand that reality. I was being told I couldn't access my own equity despite clearly having the financial capacity to support the refinanced mortgage and use the capital productively."</p><p>Experiencing similar frustration accessing your equity?<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call/"> Schedule a call</a> to discuss alternative solutions.</p><h2><b>The Discovery: How Rachel Found Bank Statement Cash-Out Refinancing</b></h2><p>While discussing her business expansion challenges at a local Chamber of Commerce networking event, Rachel mentioned her frustration with conventional refinance lenders to another business owner who operated multiple retail locations. The owner immediately recognized Rachel's situation—she'd faced identical challenges years earlier when expanding her own business. She enthusiastically recommended exploring bank statement loan programs designed specifically for business owners with strong deposits but tax-minimized income.</p><h3><b>How Did Rachel Discover Bank Statement Loan Cash-Out Refinance Programs?</b></h3><p>"She told me her story, and it was like looking in a mirror," Rachel explained. "Multiple rejections from conventional lenders who couldn't see past tax returns. Strong business cash flow that banks ignored. The desperate feeling of being trapped by smart tax planning. Then she explained how bank statement loans changed everything—qualifying based on actual business deposits rather than tax return income. I was skeptical after three rejections, but desperate enough to try anything."</p><p>Following the recommendation, Rachel scheduled a consultation with a loan advisor specializing in alternative documentation cash-out refinancing for business owners and entrepreneurs. She honestly expected another explanation of why her situation "didn't qualify" or another request for extensive documentation she couldn't provide. Instead, the conversation revealed a completely different approach to evaluating her financial capacity.</p><h3><b>How Do Bank Statement Loan Cash-Out Refinance Programs Work Differently?</b></h3><p>The advisor explained how bank statement cash-out refinancing works fundamentally differently than conventional mortgages. Instead of analyzing tax returns and focusing on taxable income after all business deductions, bank statement lenders evaluate actual business bank deposits over extended periods. They calculate average monthly deposits, analyze consistency and trends, apply standard expense ratios to account for operating costs, and determine qualifying income based on actual business cash flow rather than tax-optimized reported income.</p><p>"For the first time in weeks, I felt genuine hope," Rachel said. "Someone was actually willing to look at my real business performance instead of just my tax forms. The advisor explained that with my consistent business deposits over many years, I could potentially qualify for the cash-out amount I needed to open my second location. The bank statement lender would focus on my actual cash flow—which was more than strong enough to support both my existing store operations and a larger mortgage payment. This approach finally made sense for business owners like me who run profitable businesses but take legitimate tax deductions."</p><h3><b>What Made Bank Statement Loan Cash-Out Refinance Ideal for Rachel's Situation?</b></h3><p>The advisor also helped Rachel understand why bank statement loans work particularly well for retail business owners, restaurant operators, service businesses, and other entrepreneurs with strong cash flow but tax-minimized income. These programs recognize that business owners structure their finances to optimize tax efficiency while maintaining real, verifiable income through consistent business deposits.</p><p>Rachel learned she could potentially access substantial equity based on her business bank deposits rather than her tax return income—unlocking the capital she needed for strategic expansion while maintaining favorable mortgage terms compared to alternative business financing options.</p><h2><b>The Solution: Bank Statement Loan Cash-Out Refinance Approval Process</b></h2><p>Rachel worked with her loan advisor to assemble the required documentation for a bank statement loan cash-out refinance application. Unlike traditional mortgages requiring two years of complete tax returns with all schedules analyzed for every line item, the bank statement loan program focused on her actual business deposit history demonstrating consistent cash flow performance.</p><h3><b>What Documentation Did Rachel Provide for Bank Statement Loan Cash-Out Refinance?</b></h3><p><b>Documentation provided:</b></p><ul><li>Extended period of business bank statements showing consistent monthly deposits from retail sales</li><li>Personal bank statements demonstrating appropriate financial reserves</li><li>Business license and documentation confirming operations over many years</li><li>Excellent credit score with spotless payment history across all accounts</li><li>Current mortgage balance and home appraisal showing substantial built-in equity</li><li>Detailed business plan for second location with market analysis and financial projections</li><li>Proof of lease availability for new retail space with favorable terms</li><li>Profit and loss statement prepared by accountant (supplementary documentation)</li><li>Strong personal financial reserves exceeding lender requirements</li><li>Letter from accountant confirming business stability and expansion strategy viability</li></ul><h3><b>How Long Does Bank Statement Loan Cash-Out Refinance Approval Take?</b></h3><p><b>The approval process:</b></p><ol><li><b>Initial consultation</b> — Discussed cash-out refinance goals and bank statement qualification approach</li><li><b>Pre-qualification</b> — Reviewed deposit patterns and estimated available equity access</li><li><b>Business plan review</b> — Analyzed expansion strategy and capital deployment plan</li><li><b>Document submission</b> — Uploaded business and personal bank statements through secure portal</li><li><b>Deposit analysis</b> — Bank statement lender calculated average monthly deposits and applied expense ratios</li><li><b>Income verification</b> — Confirmed qualifying income based on business cash flow patterns</li><li><b>Credit review</b> — Verified excellent credit score and payment history</li><li><b>Property appraisal</b> — Scheduled professional home appraisal to determine current value</li><li><b>Appraisal completion</b> — Home appraised at strong value confirming substantial available equity</li><li><b>Underwriting analysis</b> — Final file review including business viability and repayment capacity</li><li><b>Conditional approval</b> — Approved for cash-out amount needed, pending final documentation</li><li><b>Clear to close</b> — All conditions satisfied, closing scheduled</li><li><b>Closing</b> — Funded cash-out refinance with capital for business expansion</li></ol><p>The bank statement lender analyzed Rachel's business bank statements over an extended period, calculated average monthly deposits, applied standard expense ratios, and determined her qualifying income at a level sufficient to approve both the refinanced mortgage and the substantial cash-out proceeds she needed—significantly higher than traditional lenders calculated using her tax returns showing reduced income after legitimate business deductions.</p><h3><b>What Made Rachel's Bank Statement Loan Cash-Out Refinance Successful?</b></h3><p>"The bank statement loan cash-out refinance process was thorough but focused on what actually mattered—my business performance," Rachel explained. "They analyzed my deposit history, verified consistency, evaluated my expansion plans, and approved my application. Within several weeks, I had the capital I needed to open my second location. The bank statement approach recognized my real financial capacity when conventional lenders couldn't see past my tax-optimized returns."</p><p>Exploring refinance?<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/refinance-or-heloc-inquiry/"> Submit a refinance inquiry</a> to compare your options.</p><h2><b>The Results: Rachel Opens Second Location Successfully</b></h2><p>Rachel successfully closed on her bank statement loan cash-out refinance approximately six weeks from initial application. She accessed substantial equity from her home through the refinance, providing the capital needed to open her second boutique location in the high-traffic shopping district she'd targeted.</p><h3><b>What Results Did Rachel Achieve with Bank Statement Loan Cash-Out Refinance?</b></h3><p><b>Final refinance outcome:</b></p><ul><li>Home appraised at strong current market value showing significant appreciation</li><li>New mortgage at competitive interest rate for cash-out refinancing</li><li>Favorable long-term fixed-rate structure providing payment stability</li><li>Substantial cash-out proceeds for business expansion capital</li><li>Timeline: Application to closing in approximately six weeks</li><li>Property: Primary residence, Naples, FL</li><li>Equity accessed for strategic business growth without business loan restrictions</li><li>Lower financing costs compared to business loans or alternative capital sources</li><li>No ownership dilution or investor demands</li><li>Full control of expansion strategy maintained</li></ul><p><b>Business expansion results:</b></p><ul><li>Second location opened on schedule in prime retail district</li><li>Strong initial sales performance exceeding projections</li><li>Inventory procurement completed for both locations</li><li>Professional store design and fixtures installed</li><li>Point-of-sale systems integrated across both stores</li><li>Quality staff hired and trained for new location</li><li>Marketing campaign launched successfully</li><li>Brand presence expanded significantly in Naples market</li></ul><h3><b>How Did Bank Statement Loan Cash-Out Refinance Compare to Traditional Financing?</b></h3><p><b>Traditional cash-out refinancing vs. bank statement loan qualification:</b></p><ul><li><b>Traditional lender qualification:</b> Rejected—insufficient borrowing power based on tax returns</li><li><b>Bank statement loan qualification:</b> Approved for substantial cash-out amount needed</li><li><b>Capital access:</b> Significantly higher with bank statement approach</li><li><b>Business expansion goal:</b> ACHIEVED ✓</li><li><b>Tax strategy:</b> Unchanged—Rachel continues maximizing legitimate deductions</li><li><b>Business ownership:</b> Maintained—no investors or lenders controlling operations</li><li><b>Financing costs:</b> More favorable than business loans or alternative funding</li></ul><p>Rachel's new mortgage provides the capital she needed at favorable terms compared to business financing alternatives. The cash-out proceeds funded her second location opening completely, allowing her to negotiate with suppliers for better inventory pricing through increased volume purchasing, hire experienced retail staff, and invest in professional store design that matches her brand standards.</p><h3><b>What Are Rachel's Long-Term Plans After Bank Statement Loan Cash-Out Refinance Success?</b></h3><p>"The bank statement loan cash-out refinance made my expansion possible when conventional lenders said no," Rachel explained. "Within months of opening the second location, we exceeded our sales projections. The new store generates strong revenue and is already profitable ahead of schedule. Without this financing, I would have either missed the prime retail location opportunity or been forced into expensive business loans with restrictive terms and personal guarantees limiting my flexibility."</p><p>Rachel views this expansion as a critical step in building a multi-location retail brand that will eventually provide generational wealth for her family. Her goal is to open a third location within the next few years, continuing to grow her business strategically through high-traffic retail spaces in affluent markets.</p><p>"This isn't just about two stores instead of one," Rachel added. "This is about building a retail brand with multiple locations that creates real wealth and eventually provides legacy for my children. The bank statement loan cash-out refinance gave me access to capital on favorable terms without diluting ownership or accepting restrictive loan covenants. I maintained complete control of my expansion strategy and business decisions."</p><p>When Rachel is ready to open location three, she may pursue another bank statement loan cash-out refinance if additional equity has built up, or she may explore using operating cash flow from her now-two profitable locations. She also plans to investigate<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/heloc/"> HELOC</a> or<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/home-equity-loan/"> Home Equity Loan</a> options that would allow her to access equity without refinancing her current favorable mortgage rate—preserving her low rate while still accessing capital for future growth.</p><p>"The best part is I didn't have to change how I run my business or how my accountant structures my taxes," Rachel said. "I continue taking every legitimate business deduction, minimizing tax liability, and operating profitably—while still having access to financing when I need capital for strategic growth. The bank statement loan program recognizes the reality of how successful business owners operate financially. It's the smart way to build wealth through business ownership while leveraging home equity strategically."</p><p>Ready to get started?<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/same-day-approval/"> Get approved</a> or<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call/"> schedule a call</a> to discuss your situation.</p><h2><b>Exploring Other Bank Statement Loan Options?</b></h2><p>While Rachel used a bank statement loan cash-out refinance for business expansion, this financing works for multiple scenarios:</p><ul><li>Need to purchase investment property? See how<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/case-studies/bank-statement-loan-purchase"> a restaurant owner used bank statement loan purchase for first rental</a></li><li>Want to reduce monthly payments? See how<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/case-studies/bank-statement-loan-refinance/"> a contractor achieved savings with bank statement loan refinance</a></li><li><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/case-studies/">View all case studies</a> to find stories matching your situation</li></ul><h2><b>Key Takeaways for Business Owners Considering Bank Statement Loan Cash-Out Refinance</b></h2><h3><b>What Can Entrepreneurs Learn from This Bank Statement Loan Cash-Out Refinance Success?</b></h3><ul><li><b>Bank statement loans qualify borrowers based on business deposits, not tax returns</b>—allowing business owners to maintain tax-efficient structures while accessing home equity for strategic purposes (<a href="https://www.irs.gov/publications/p535">IRS business expense guidelines</a>)</li><li><b>Cash-out refinancing can fund business expansion more favorably than business loans</b>—lower rates, no ownership dilution, no restrictive covenants, full control maintained (<a href="https://www.sba.gov/business-guide/plan-your-business/fund-your-business">SBA business financing resources</a>)</li><li><b>Consistent deposit patterns over extended periods strengthen applications</b>—bank statement lenders analyze average monthly deposits and trend stability demonstrating sustainable business performance</li><li><b>Cash-intensive businesses benefit especially from bank statement qualification</b>—retail stores, restaurants, service businesses with substantial deposits but legitimate tax deductions qualify more easily</li><li><b>Strong credit profiles unlock competitive rates even with alternative documentation</b>—Rachel's excellent credit helped secure favorable pricing despite using bank deposits rather than tax returns for bank statement loan cash-out refinance</li><li><b>Business expansion funded through home equity preserves ownership and control</b>—no investors demanding board seats, no lenders imposing operational restrictions, full strategic flexibility maintained</li><li><b>Think beyond a single expansion</b>—successful business owners view equity access strategically as part of a larger wealth-building plan. Rachel's goal isn't just two stores; it's building a multi-location retail brand that creates generational wealth for her family through business growth and real estate appreciation</li></ul><p>Have questions about using home equity to fund business ventures?<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call/"> Schedule a call</a> with a loan advisor experienced in business owner financing.</p><h2><b>Alternative Loan Programs for Business Owners</b></h2><p>If a bank statement loan cash-out refinance isn't the perfect fit, consider these alternatives:</p><ul><li><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/1099-loan/">1099 Loan</a> – Cash-out refinance using 1099 income for independent contractors</li><li><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/asset-based-loan/">Asset-Based Loan</a> – Qualify based on liquid investment portfolios for high-net-worth business owners</li><li><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/dscr-loan/">DSCR Loan</a> – Investment property financing based on rental income</li><li><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/heloc/">HELOC</a> – Access equity through flexible line of credit without refinancing</li><li><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/home-equity-loan/">Home Equity Loan</a> – Fixed-rate second lien to access equity while preserving first mortgage</li><li><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/business-financing">Business Line of Credit</a> – Alternative business funding through commercial lending</li></ul><p><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/">Explore all loan programs</a> to find your best option.</p><h2><b>Helpful Bank Statement Loan Cash-Out Refinance Resources</b></h2><p><b>Learn more about this loan program:</b></p><ul><li><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/bank-statement-loan/">Complete Bank Statement Loan Guide</a> - Detailed requirements and qualification guidelines</li><li><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-calculator/bank-statement-loan-calculator">Bank Statement Loan Calculator</a> - Estimate how much equity you can access based on deposits</li></ul><p><b>Similar success stories:</b></p><ul><li><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/case-studies/bank-statement-loan-purchase">How a restaurant owner purchased first rental with bank statement loan</a> - Investment property purchase</li><li><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/case-studies/bank-statement-loan-refinance/">Contractor's bank statement refinance success</a> - Reducing monthly payments</li><li><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/case-studies/">View all case studies</a> - Browse by business type and goals</li></ul><p><b>External authoritative resources:</b></p><ul><li><a href="https://www.irs.gov/publications/p535">IRS business expense guidelines</a> - Understanding legitimate business deductions</li><li><a href="https://www.sba.gov/business-guide/plan-your-business/fund-your-business">SBA business financing resources</a> - Small Business Administration funding guidance</li></ul><p><b>Ready to get started?</b></p><ul><li><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/same-day-approval/">Apply online</a> - Start your cash-out refinance application today</li><li><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call/">Schedule a consultation</a> - Discuss your business funding strategy</li><li><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/discovery-quiz/">Take the discovery quiz</a> - Clarify your business and wealth-building goals</li></ul><p>Need local expertise?<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/get-a-local-introduction/"> Get introduced to trusted partners</a> including business advisors, CPAs, and commercial real estate specialists.</p><p><b>Disclosure:</b> <a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/nexa-mortgage-partnership/"  data-wpil-monitor-id="312">NEXA Mortgage</a>, LLC dba Stairway Mortgage — NMLS #1660690 • Equal Housing Lender. Applications are handled by state-licensed Mortgage Loan Originators; you will be matched with an MLO licensed in your state. Not all products are available in all states. See our<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/licenses-disclosures"> Licenses &amp; Disclosures</a> page for state-specific information. This case study is for educational and illustrative purposes only. Scenarios, borrowers, and loan terms may be hypothetical and are used to demonstrate potential financing solutions. Not a commitment to lend. All loans are subject to credit approval, program availability, and underwriting guidelines. Interest rates, fees, loan amounts, and other terms are examples and do not represent current offers or market rates. Actual terms vary by applicant profile, property, market conditions, and lender guidelines, and may change without notice. Bank statement loans typically require extended periods of business or personal bank statements showing consistent deposits. Using home equity to fund business ventures involves risk; businesses may fail, and borrowers remain obligated to repay mortgages regardless of business outcomes. Texas homestead cash-out refinance is limited by state law and subject to additional regulations including waiting periods before closing. For current terms specific to your situation, please<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call/"> schedule a consultation</a> or<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/same-day-approval/"> apply online</a>. NMLS Consumer Access: https://www.nmlsconsumeraccess.org/</p>		
